[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Bath-sheba, the daughter of Eliam.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Her name is spelt in Chronicles ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Bath-shua, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and her father’s name is said to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ammiel. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ammiel and Eliam are the same name with its component parts transposed, as Scripture names are often varied: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God’s people ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the people of God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Wife of Uriah the Hittite.—His name appears (2Samuel 23:39) in the list of David’s thirty chief heroes, and the whole story represents him as a brave and noble-minded soldier. David had now given rein to his guilty passion so far that the knowledge of Bath-sheba’s being a married woman, and the wife of one of his chief warriors, does not check him.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Wife of Uriah the Hittite.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—His name appears (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 23:39",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") in the list of David’s thirty chief heroes, and the whole story represents him as a brave and noble-minded soldier. David had now given rein to his guilty passion so far that the knowledge of Bath-sheba’s being a married woman, and the wife of one of his chief warriors, does not check him.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Samuel 11:3",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 11:3",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "David sent and inquired after the woman — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Thus, instead of suppressing that desire which the sight of his eyes had kindled, he seeks rather to feed it; and first inquires who she was; that if she were unmarried he might make her either his wife or his concubine. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And one said, Is not this Bath-sheba? — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This seems to have been an answer given by some one to David’s inquiry. Uriah is called a Hittite, because he was such by nation, but a proselyte to the Jewish religion; and for his valour made one of the king’s guards among the Cherethites and the Pelethites; which was the reason, perhaps, that he had a house so near the king’s. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "11:1-5 Observe the occasions of David's sin; what led to it. 1. Neglect of his business. He tarried at Jerusalem. When we are out of the way of our duty, we are in temptation. 2. Love of ease: idleness gives great advantage to the tempter. 3. A wandering eye. He had not, like Job, made a covenant with his eyes, or, at this time, he had forgotten it. And observe the steps of the sin. See how the way of sin is down-hill; when men begin to do evil, they cannot soon stop. Observe the aggravations of the sin. How could David rebuke or punish that in others, of which he was conscious that he himself was guilty?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
